{"title_page": "Chang-Shou Lin", "text_new": "'''Chang-Shou Lin''' ({{zh|t=\u6797\u9577\u58fd}}; born 17 April 1951) is a Taiwanese mathematician.\n\nLin completed his bachelor's and master's degrees in mathematics at [[National Taiwan University]].<ref name=\"as\"/> He then completed doctoral study at [[Columbia University]] in the United States in 1983,<ref name=\"as\">{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://academicians.sinica.edu.tw/index.php?r=academician-n%2Fshow&id=215&_lang=en |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Academia Sinica}}</ref> and was a member of the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] between 1984 and 1985.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/chang-shou-lin |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Institute of Advanced Study}}</ref> He taught at NTU from 1987 to 1990, when he joined the faculty of [[National Chung Cheng University]].<ref name=\"as\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=http://math.cts.nthu.edu.tw/Mathematics/academic_c/CSLin.html |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=National Tsing Hua University}}</ref> Lin was director of the National Center for Theoretical Sciences between 1993 and 2003.<ref name=\"as\"/> In 2006, Lin returned to NTU as director of the  Institute for Mathematical Sciences.<ref name=\"as\"/>\n\nIn his research, Lin has explored [[mean field theory]] and [[Eisenstein series]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lakeside lectures Speaker: Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://www.math.sinica.edu.tw/www/poster_upload/20150504-Lakeside.pdf |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Instutite of Mathematics, Academia Sinica |date=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dubedat |first1=Julien |title=Nov. 18: Chang-Shou Lin (National Taiwan U.) |url=https://www.math.columbia.edu/2015/10/23/nov-18-chang-shou-lin-national-taiwan-u/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Columbia University |date=23 October 2015}}</ref> Lin was elected a member of [[Academia Sinica]] in 1998,  received the [[Morningside Medal]] that same year, and was awarded Taiwan's {{ill|Presidential Science Prize|zh|\u7e3d\u7d71\u79d1\u5b78\u734e}} in 2001.<ref name=\"as\"/> He is an editor of the ''Bulletin of the Institute of Mathematics'', published by Academia Sinica.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bulletin of the Institute of Mathematics |url=https://web.math.sinica.edu.tw/bulletin/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Institute of Mathematics, Academia Sinica}}</ref> In 2014, Lin [[List of International Congresses of Mathematicians Plenary and Invited Speakers|was invited to speak]] at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] conference in Seoul, South Korea. \n\nLin was critical of the [[Democratic Progressive Party]] response to the [[Sunflower Student Movement]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Chang-shou |title=DPP\u2019s reaction to protest is troubling |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2014/04/12/2003587825 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=12 April 2014}}</ref> and has signed petitions backing required mathematics education for Taiwanese senior high school students,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=I-chia |title=Academicians upset by planned math cuts |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2014/06/05/2003592023 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=5 June 2014}}</ref> and against the nuclear energy question posed by the [[2018 Taiwanese referendum]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Rachel |title=Academics push petition against key referendum |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/11/05/2003703619 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lin, Chang-shou}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Sinica]]\n[[Category:National Chung Cheng University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University alumni]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University faculty]]\n{{Taiwan-scientist-stub}}\n{{mathematician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Chang-Shou Lin''' ({{zh|t=\u6797\u9577\u58fd}}; born 17 April 1951) is a Taiwanese mathematician.\n\nLin completed his bachelor's and master's degrees in mathematics at [[National Taiwan University]].<ref name=\"as\"/> He then completed doctoral study at [[Columbia University]] in the United States in 1983,<ref name=\"as\">{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://academicians.sinica.edu.tw/index.php?r=academician-n%2Fshow&id=215&_lang=en |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Academia Sinica}}</ref> and was a member of the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] between 1984 and 1985.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/chang-shou-lin |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Instutute of Advanced Study}}</ref> He taught at NTU from 1987 to 1990, when he joined the faculty of [[National Chung Cheng University]].<ref name=\"as\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Chang-Shou Lin |url=http://math.cts.nthu.edu.tw/Mathematics/academic_c/CSLin.html |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=National Tsing Hua University}}</ref> Lin was director of the National Center for Theoretical Sciences between 1993 and 2003.<ref name=\"as\"/> In 2006, Lin returned to NTU as director of the  Institute for Mathematical Sciences.<ref name=\"as\"/>\n\nIn his research, Lin has explored [[mean field theory]] and [[Eisenstein series]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lakeside lectures Speaker: Chang-Shou Lin |url=https://www.math.sinica.edu.tw/www/poster_upload/20150504-Lakeside.pdf |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Instutite of Mathematics, Academia Sinica |date=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dubedat |first1=Julien |title=Nov. 18: Chang-Shou Lin (National Taiwan U.) |url=https://www.math.columbia.edu/2015/10/23/nov-18-chang-shou-lin-national-taiwan-u/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Columbia University |date=23 October 2015}}</ref> Lin was elected a member of [[Academia Sinica]] in 1998,  received the [[Morningside Medal]] that same year, and was awarded Taiwan's {{ill|Presidential Science Prize|zh|\u7e3d\u7d71\u79d1\u5b78\u734e}} in 2001.<ref name=\"as\"/> He is an editor of the ''Bulletin of the Institute of Mathematics'', published by Academia Sinica.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bulletin of the Institute of Mathematics |url=https://web.math.sinica.edu.tw/bulletin/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |publisher=Institute of Mathematics, Academia Sinica}}</ref> In 2014, Lin [[List of International Congresses of Mathematicians Plenary and Invited Speakers|was invited to speak]] at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] conference in Seoul, South Korea. \n\nLin was critical of the [[Democratic Progressive Party]] response to the [[Sunflower Student Movement]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Chang-shou |title=DPP\u2019s reaction to protest is troubling |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2014/04/12/2003587825 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=12 April 2014}}</ref> and has signed petitions backing required mathematics education for Taiwanese senior high school students,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=I-chia |title=Academicians upset by planned math cuts |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2014/06/05/2003592023 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=5 June 2014}}</ref> and against the nuclear energy question posed by the [[2018 Taiwanese referendum]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Rachel |title=Academics push petition against key referendum |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/11/05/2003703619 |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Taipei Times |date=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lin, Chang-shou}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Sinica]]\n[[Category:National Chung Cheng University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University alumni]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University faculty]]\n{{Taiwan-scientist-stub}}\n{{mathematician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chang-Shou_Lin"}
{"title_page": "Isi Leibler", "text_new": "{{short description|Jewish activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Isi Leibler\n|image = Isi_Leibler.jpg\n|caption = Isi Leibler, 2011\n|birth_date  = 1934 \n|birth_place = [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]]\n}}\n\n'''Isi Leibler''' (Hebrew: {{Hebrew|\u05d0\u05d9\u05d6\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05d1\u05dc\u05e8}}; born 1934) is a Belgian-born Australian-Israeli international Jewish activist.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]], Leibler was brought to [[Australia]] by his parents as an infant just before the outbreak of World War II. Leibler served as president of the [[Executive Council of Australian Jewry]] and Chairman of the Governing Board of the [[World Jewish Congress]]. He was a leader in the global campaign on behalf of Soviet Jewry and played a role in the lead-up to Israeli diplomatic relations between India and China.\n\nLiebler and his wife moved to [[Israel]] in 1999, settling in [[Jerusalem]]. He writes weekly columns in the [[Jerusalem Post]], the Hebrew daily [[Israel Hayom]], and on his blog Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem.<ref>Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem www.wordfromjerusalem.com</ref>\n\nLiebler married Naomi Porush in 1958, and the couple had three sons and a daughter. All of his children and most of their families also live in Israel.\n\n==Australian Jewry==\nDescribed in the new edition of [[Encyclopaedia Judaica]] as \u201cunquestionably the dominant Jewish lay leader in Australia during the previous quarter century\u201d,<ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica (2006) as quoted in Jewish Virtual Library https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01621.html</ref> Leibler occupied the leadership of the Australian Jewish community ([[Executive Council of Australian Jewry]]) from 1978 and served four terms in this office, retiring in 1995.\n\n==Soviet Jewry==\nLeibler involvement in the fight for Soviet Jewry was first solicited by [[Shaul Avigur]], the head of [[Nativ (liaison bureau)|Nativ]] (the then-covert agency dealing with Soviet Jews) who played an enormous role behind the scenes in the formulation of policy during the early years of the state.<ref>http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Columnists/Article.aspx?id=193595</ref> In 1962, Mr. Leibler engineered a public campaign which resulted in Australia becoming the first country in the world to raise the plight of Soviet Jewry at the [[United Nations]]. In 1965, he published ''Soviet Jewry and Human Rights''.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=321</ref>\n\nBefore the collapse of the Soviet Empire, Leibler made numerous visits to the [[Soviet Union]] and developed close associations with the leading Jewish dissidents and refuseniks, which he still maintains in Israel. The visits came to an end in 1980 with his arrest and expulsion from the Soviet Union.\n\nWhen [[Gorbachev]] liberalised the system, Leibler became the first international Jewish leader to be invited to the Soviet Union to evaluate the changes. He subsequently launched the first Jewish cultural centre in the Soviet Union \u2013 the Solomon Mykhoels Centre in Moscow,<ref>A Jewish Center, Officially Approved, Will Open in Moscow, New York Times February 1989 https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/08/world/a-jewish-center-officially-approved-will-open-in-moscow.html?scp=1&sq=isi%20leibler%20soviet&st=cse</ref> together with the first Hebrew Song Festivals in Moscow and Leningrad.\n\nLeibler\u2019s activities and campaign  on behalf of Soviet Jewry are documented  in the book: Let my People Go: The untold story of Australia and Soviet Jews 1969 \u2013 1989, authored by Sam Lipski and Suzanne Rutland in 2015.<ref>Let My People Go: untold story of Australia and Soviet Jews http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/let-my-people-go-untold-story-of-australia-and-soviet-jews/news-story/1fc3aa69b018f589a3a0eec04178d8e1</ref>\n\n==Asia Pacific==\nFollowing the liberation of Soviet Jewry, Leibler focused his attention on the Asia-Pacific region. He met with Indian Prime Minister Narasimha Rao and Chinese Foreign Minister [[Qian Qichen]] ahead of the establishment of diplomatic relations between Israel and both countries. Leibler also convened a colloquium for leading Jewish and Chinese scholars in Beijing prior to diplomatic relations being instituted between Israel and China.\n\n==World Jewish Congress==\nLeibler occupied senior roles in the [[World Jewish Congress]] (WJC), an umbrella organisation representing global Jewry, including Chairman of the Governing Board and Senior Vice President.\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2004 Leibler confronted the leadership of the WJC over the issue of governance, financial transparency, and financial irregularities. The conflict between Leibler and WJC Chairman [[Israel Singer]] revolved around the former's demand for an investigation into the transfer of $1.2 million from the organization's New York headquarters to a bank account in Geneva, and the subsequent transfer of the money by Singer into a trust account held by his friend.<ref>Money shifting uproar shakes World Jewish Congress, New York Times November 2004 https://www.nytimes.com/2004/11/30/national/30charity.html?</ref> Leibler's calls for a comprehensive independent audit\" brought him into conflict with Singer and Edgar Bronfman, the WJC's longtime \"president, chief benefactor, and guiding force.\"<ref>Machers in meltdown, New York Magazine http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/politics/international/features/11158/index4.html</ref>\n\nIn January 2005, Leibler resigned as WJC vice president, telling Haaretz that he \"came to the conclusion that I cannot remain in an organization that requires me to give a stamp of approval to activities I deem inappropriate.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/news/world-jewish-congress-vice-president-isi-leibler-resigns-1.146736</ref> Elan Steinberg also left the WJC amidst the controversy, while two other top officials were fired.<ref>The Forward http://www.forward.com/articles/10915/</ref> Leibler wrote that his position had been \"vindicated\" but expressed \"deep sadness\" at the organization's disarray.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=279</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[New York State Attorney General]]'s Office began an investigation into the WJC.<ref>Stephanie Strom, [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/31/national/31charity.html Spitzer Looking Into World Jewish Congress], ''New York Times'' (December 31, 2004).</ref> The AG's Office issued a report in 2006 that found \"serious financial mismanagement\" at WJC, including improper payments and loans to Singer.<ref name=\"EdenPopper\">Ami Eden & Nathaniel Popper, [http://www.forward.com/articles/1583/ N.Y. Probe of Charity Cites Mismanagement], ''Jewish Daily Forward'' (February 3, 2006).</ref> Under an agreement between the Attorney General's Office and WJC, Singer was barred from the organization's leadership roles and returned several loans and payments, and the WJC undertook reforms.<ref name=\"EdenPopper\"/><ref>Ruben Brosbe, [http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=11927 WJC leader banned from fiscal duties], Associated Press (February 1, 2006).</ref> The WJC subsequently filed a $6 million defamation suit against Leibler in the Israeli courts but were withdrew the action less than six months later, and were ordered by the court to pay Leibler's legal expenses.<ref>Amiram Barkat, [http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/features/the-dollar-account-and-the-removal-of-the-whistle-blower-leibler-1.213677 The Dollar Account and the Removal of the Whistle-blower Leibler], ''Haaretz'' (February 22, 2007).</ref> A [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] audit in 2006 submitted by the WJC to the AG's Office found that the financial scancel was \"significantly broader than has been publicly known,\" with some $3 million unaccounted for from 1994 to 2004.<ref name=\"Popper\">Nathaniel Popper, [http://forward.com/news/7414/wjc-audit-4-million-unaccounted-for/ WJC Audit: $3 Million Unaccounted For], ''Jewish Daily Forward'' (November 3, 2006).</ref> Leibler, described by the ''Jewish Daily Forward'' as the \"most persistent critic\" of the WJC, said that these findings were not surprising.<ref name=\"Popper\"/>\n\nLeibler has been accused of de-legitimizing liberal Jewish supporters of Israel.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/blogs/strenger-than-fiction/memo-to-jewish-haters-of-liberals-the-middle-ages-are-over-1.4863</ref> Leibler responded that \"I stand by my view that those whose primary goal is to delegitimize and demonize the Jewish state should be marginalized from the mainstream Jewish community. That is not fascism. It is common sense.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/news/response-on-exorcising-israel-bashers-from-the-jewish-mainstream-1.4421</ref>\n\nLeibler has called for a full external investigation and disclosure of massive misappropriations of funds at the [[Conference on Jewish Material Claims Against Germany]] ([[Claims Conference]]), citing allegations of incompetence, impropriety and cover-ups, the absence of an independent review board, bureaucratization and a domination by a small clique, along with a failure to \"prioritize the needs of survivors, who are now elderly and many of whom are living in dire poverty.<ref>At the expnse of survivors; Israel Hayom as quoted in Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=2513</ref> In response Claims Conference [[Julius Berman]] has accused Leibler of engaging \"in irresponsible invective and baseless charges against an organization that for nearly 60 years has been the leading international advocate for the rights of Holocaust victims.\"<ref>Jerusalem Post http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Editorials/Article.aspx?id=182969</ref>\n\n==Publications and Writings==\nLeibler is a weekly columnist to the [[Jerusalem Post]].<ref>[https://bazonline.ch/infografik/schweiz/nie-wieder/story/22033812 Conversation ''Nie wieder!''] with Markus Sommer, [[Basler Zeitung]], November 24, 2018</ref>  He is also a regular columnist for [[Israel Hayom]], the Israeli daily newspaper.\n\nLeibler has written on the dangers of religious extremism, in particular radical religious nationalism.<ref>Retreat into irrelevance http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=848</ref><ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=3821</ref>\n\nLeibler is the author of ''The Israel-Diaspora Identity Crisis: A Looming Disaster''.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=312</ref>\n\nLeibler now chairs the Israel Diaspora Committee of the [[Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs]], an Israeli think tank.<ref>Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs http://www.jcpa.org/JCPA/Templates/ShowPage.asp?DBID=1&TMID=610&LNGID=1&FID=253&PID=0&IID=1721</ref>\n\nLeibler also published a study on the threat post Zionism poses to the soul of Israel, titled ''Is the Dream Ending?<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=1145</ref>\n\n==Business==\nIn Australia, Leibler\u2019s company, Jetset Tours, was the largest travel organization in the region with branches throughout the world. He was also a director one of Australia\u2019s three national television companies. In Israel he has invested and acts as a consultant to a number of high tech companies\n\n==Awards==\nLeibler was appointed a CBE ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]])<ref>http://www.ajcarchives.org/AJC_DATA/Files/1982_13_Australia.pdf</ref> in 1977, an AO ([[Officer of the Order of Australia]]) in 1989 and an honorary Doctor of Letters from [[Deakin University]] in 1990. In 2015, Leibler was awarded an honorary doctorate from [[Bar-Ilan University]] in recognition of \u201chis tireless efforts to address the challenges facing the Jewish nation at every historic crossroad\u201d.<ref>Bar-Ilan University Honors Australian-Israeli Jewish Leader Isi Leibler http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=33&pt=20&pid=117&level=2&cPath=33&type=1&news=2719</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leibler, Isi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:People from Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Belgian emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Belgian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Zionists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Jewish activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Isi Leibler\n|image = Isi_Leibler.jpg\n|caption = Isi Leibler, 2011\n|birth_date  = 1934 \n|birth_place = [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]]\n}}\n\n'''Isi Leibler''' (born 1934) is a Belgian-born Australian-Israeli international Jewish activist.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]], Leibler was brought to [[Australia]] by his parents as an infant just before the outbreak of World War II. Leibler served as president of the [[Executive Council of Australian Jewry]] and Chairman of the Governing Board of the [[World Jewish Congress]]. He was a leader in the global campaign on behalf of Soviet Jewry and played a role in the lead-up to Israeli diplomatic relations between India and China.\n\nLiebler and his wife moved to [[Israel]] in 1999, settling in [[Jerusalem]]. He writes weekly columns in the [[Jerusalem Post]], the Hebrew daily [[Israel Hayom]], and on his blog Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem.<ref>Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem www.wordfromjerusalem.com</ref>\n\nLiebler married Naomi Porush in 1958, and the couple had three sons and a daughter. All of his children and most of their families also live in Israel.\n\n==Australian Jewry==\nDescribed in the new edition of [[Encyclopaedia Judaica]] as \u201cunquestionably the dominant Jewish lay leader in Australia during the previous quarter century\u201d,<ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica (2006) as quoted in Jewish Virtual Library https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0002_0_01621.html</ref> Leibler occupied the leadership of the Australian Jewish community ([[Executive Council of Australian Jewry]]) from 1978 and served four terms in this office, retiring in 1995.\n\n==Soviet Jewry==\nLeibler involvement in the fight for Soviet Jewry was first solicited by [[Shaul Avigur]], the head of [[Nativ (liaison bureau)|Nativ]] (the then-covert agency dealing with Soviet Jews) who played an enormous role behind the scenes in the formulation of policy during the early years of the state.<ref>http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Columnists/Article.aspx?id=193595</ref> In 1962, Mr. Leibler engineered a public campaign which resulted in Australia becoming the first country in the world to raise the plight of Soviet Jewry at the [[United Nations]]. In 1965, he published ''Soviet Jewry and Human Rights''.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=321</ref>\n\nBefore the collapse of the Soviet Empire, Leibler made numerous visits to the [[Soviet Union]] and developed close associations with the leading Jewish dissidents and refuseniks, which he still maintains in Israel. The visits came to an end in 1980 with his arrest and expulsion from the Soviet Union.\n\nWhen [[Gorbachev]] liberalised the system, Leibler became the first international Jewish leader to be invited to the Soviet Union to evaluate the changes. He subsequently launched the first Jewish cultural centre in the Soviet Union \u2013 the Solomon Mykhoels Centre in Moscow,<ref>A Jewish Center, Officially Approved, Will Open in Moscow, New York Times February 1989 https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/08/world/a-jewish-center-officially-approved-will-open-in-moscow.html?scp=1&sq=isi%20leibler%20soviet&st=cse</ref> together with the first Hebrew Song Festivals in Moscow and Leningrad.\n\nLeibler\u2019s activities and campaign  on behalf of Soviet Jewry are documented  in the book: Let my People Go: The untold story of Australia and Soviet Jews 1969 \u2013 1989, authored by Sam Lipski and Suzanne Rutland in 2015.<ref>Let My People Go: untold story of Australia and Soviet Jews http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/let-my-people-go-untold-story-of-australia-and-soviet-jews/news-story/1fc3aa69b018f589a3a0eec04178d8e1</ref>\n\n==Asia Pacific==\nFollowing the liberation of Soviet Jewry, Leibler focused his attention on the Asia-Pacific region. He met with Indian Prime Minister Narasimha Rao and Chinese Foreign Minister [[Qian Qichen]] ahead of the establishment of diplomatic relations between Israel and both countries. Leibler also convened a colloquium for leading Jewish and Chinese scholars in Beijing prior to diplomatic relations being instituted between Israel and China.\n\n==World Jewish Congress==\nLeibler occupied senior roles in the [[World Jewish Congress]] (WJC), an umbrella organisation representing global Jewry, including Chairman of the Governing Board and Senior Vice President.\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2004 Leibler confronted the leadership of the WJC over the issue of governance, financial transparency, and financial irregularities. The conflict between Leibler and WJC Chairman [[Israel Singer]] revolved around the former's demand for an investigation into the transfer of $1.2 million from the organization's New York headquarters to a bank account in Geneva, and the subsequent transfer of the money by Singer into a trust account held by his friend.<ref>Money shifting uproar shakes World Jewish Congress, New York Times November 2004 https://www.nytimes.com/2004/11/30/national/30charity.html?</ref> Leibler's calls for a comprehensive independent audit\" brought him into conflict with Singer and Edgar Bronfman, the WJC's longtime \"president, chief benefactor, and guiding force.\"<ref>Machers in meltdown, New York Magazine http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/politics/international/features/11158/index4.html</ref>\n\nIn January 2005, Leibler resigned as WJC vice president, telling Haaretz that he \"came to the conclusion that I cannot remain in an organization that requires me to give a stamp of approval to activities I deem inappropriate.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/news/world-jewish-congress-vice-president-isi-leibler-resigns-1.146736</ref> Elan Steinberg also left the WJC amidst the controversy, while two other top officials were fired.<ref>The Forward http://www.forward.com/articles/10915/</ref> Leibler wrote that his position had been \"vindicated\" but expressed \"deep sadness\" at the organization's disarray.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=279</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[New York State Attorney General]]'s Office began an investigation into the WJC.<ref>Stephanie Strom, [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/31/national/31charity.html Spitzer Looking Into World Jewish Congress], ''New York Times'' (December 31, 2004).</ref> The AG's Office issued a report in 2006 that found \"serious financial mismanagement\" at WJC, including improper payments and loans to Singer.<ref name=\"EdenPopper\">Ami Eden & Nathaniel Popper, [http://www.forward.com/articles/1583/ N.Y. Probe of Charity Cites Mismanagement], ''Jewish Daily Forward'' (February 3, 2006).</ref> Under an agreement between the Attorney General's Office and WJC, Singer was barred from the organization's leadership roles and returned several loans and payments, and the WJC undertook reforms.<ref name=\"EdenPopper\"/><ref>Ruben Brosbe, [http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=11927 WJC leader banned from fiscal duties], Associated Press (February 1, 2006).</ref> The WJC subsequently filed a $6 million defamation suit against Leibler in the Israeli courts but were withdrew the action less than six months later, and were ordered by the court to pay Leibler's legal expenses.<ref>Amiram Barkat, [http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/features/the-dollar-account-and-the-removal-of-the-whistle-blower-leibler-1.213677 The Dollar Account and the Removal of the Whistle-blower Leibler], ''Haaretz'' (February 22, 2007).</ref> A [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] audit in 2006 submitted by the WJC to the AG's Office found that the financial scancel was \"significantly broader than has been publicly known,\" with some $3 million unaccounted for from 1994 to 2004.<ref name=\"Popper\">Nathaniel Popper, [http://forward.com/news/7414/wjc-audit-4-million-unaccounted-for/ WJC Audit: $3 Million Unaccounted For], ''Jewish Daily Forward'' (November 3, 2006).</ref> Leibler, described by the ''Jewish Daily Forward'' as the \"most persistent critic\" of the WJC, said that these findings were not surprising.<ref name=\"Popper\"/>\n\nLeibler has been accused of de-legitimizing liberal Jewish supporters of Israel.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/blogs/strenger-than-fiction/memo-to-jewish-haters-of-liberals-the-middle-ages-are-over-1.4863</ref> Leibler responded that \"I stand by my view that those whose primary goal is to delegitimize and demonize the Jewish state should be marginalized from the mainstream Jewish community. That is not fascism. It is common sense.<ref>Haaretz http://www.haaretz.com/news/response-on-exorcising-israel-bashers-from-the-jewish-mainstream-1.4421</ref>\n\nLeibler has called for a full external investigation and disclosure of massive misappropriations of funds at the [[Conference on Jewish Material Claims Against Germany]] ([[Claims Conference]]), citing allegations of incompetence, impropriety and cover-ups, the absence of an independent review board, bureaucratization and a domination by a small clique, along with a failure to \"prioritize the needs of survivors, who are now elderly and many of whom are living in dire poverty.<ref>At the expnse of survivors; Israel Hayom as quoted in Candidly Speaking from Jerusalem http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=2513</ref> In response Claims Conference [[Julius Berman]] has accused Leibler of engaging \"in irresponsible invective and baseless charges against an organization that for nearly 60 years has been the leading international advocate for the rights of Holocaust victims.\"<ref>Jerusalem Post http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Editorials/Article.aspx?id=182969</ref>\n\n==Publications and Writings==\nLeibler is a weekly columnist to the [[Jerusalem Post]].<ref>[https://bazonline.ch/infografik/schweiz/nie-wieder/story/22033812 Conversation ''Nie wieder!''] with Markus Sommer, [[Basler Zeitung]], November 24, 2018</ref>  He is also a regular columnist for [[Israel Hayom]], the Israeli daily newspaper.\n\nLeibler has written on the dangers of religious extremism, in particular radical religious nationalism.<ref>Retreat into irrelevance http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=848</ref><ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?p=3821</ref>\n\nLeibler is the author of ''The Israel-Diaspora Identity Crisis: A Looming Disaster''.<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=312</ref>\n\nLeibler now chairs the Israel Diaspora Committee of the [[Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs]], an Israeli think tank.<ref>Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs http://www.jcpa.org/JCPA/Templates/ShowPage.asp?DBID=1&TMID=610&LNGID=1&FID=253&PID=0&IID=1721</ref>\n\nLeibler also published a study on the threat post Zionism poses to the soul of Israel, titled ''Is the Dream Ending?<ref>http://wordfromjerusalem.com/?page_id=1145</ref>\n\n==Business==\nIn Australia, Leibler\u2019s company, Jetset Tours, was the largest travel organization in the region with branches throughout the world. He was also a director one of Australia\u2019s three national television companies. In Israel he has invested and acts as a consultant to a number of high tech companies\n\n==Awards==\nLeibler was appointed a CBE ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]])<ref>http://www.ajcarchives.org/AJC_DATA/Files/1982_13_Australia.pdf</ref> in 1977, an AO ([[Officer of the Order of Australia]]) in 1989 and an honorary Doctor of Letters from [[Deakin University]] in 1990. In 2015, Leibler was awarded an honorary doctorate from [[Bar-Ilan University]] in recognition of \u201chis tireless efforts to address the challenges facing the Jewish nation at every historic crossroad\u201d.<ref>Bar-Ilan University Honors Australian-Israeli Jewish Leader Isi Leibler http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=33&pt=20&pid=117&level=2&cPath=33&type=1&news=2719</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leibler, Isi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:People from Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Belgian emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Belgian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Zionists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isi_Leibler"}
{"title_page": "Walter Channing (physician)", "text_new": "'''Walter Channing''' (April 15, 1786 \u2013 July 27, 1876) was an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] and [[professor]] of [[medicine]]. He was the brother of preacher [[William Ellery Channing]] and of fellow Harvard professor (of Rhetoric), [[Edward Tyrrel Channing]]. He was also the father of the poet [[William Ellery Channing (poet)|William Ellery Channing]].  He was married to Eliza Wainwright Channing from 1831 until her death in 1834.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masshist.org/collection-guides/view/fa0018 |title=Walter Channing (1786\u20131876) Papers |author=Kathleen Barker |date=March 2002 |website=[[Massachusetts Historical Society]] |accessdate=13 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], Channing entered [[Harvard University|Harvard College]] in 1804 but was expelled because of his involvement in the \"rotten cabbage brawl\" at Harvard. After studying medicine in [[Boston]] and [[Philadelphia]], he received his diploma from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and then studied at the [[University of Edinburgh]], receiving a degree there as well.  He also studied at Guy's and St. Thomas's hospitals in [[London]]. He began to practice in Boston in 1812, and in the same year became lecturer on obstetrics at Harvard.<ref name=\"Appletons\">{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Channing, William Ellery|year=1900}} Walter is the second Channing discussed in this article which mainly discusses his brother.</ref> He was the first professor of [[obstetrics]] and medical jurisprudence at [[Harvard University]] (then called Harvard College), a position he held from 1815 to 1854.<ref name=\"Baas\">{{cite book | title = Outlines of the History of Medicine and the Medical Profession | author = [[Johann Hermann Baas]] |author2=trans. Henry Ebenezer Handerson  | publisher = J.H. Vail & Co. | year = 1889 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9e8IAAAAIAAJ/page/n1108 1096] | url = https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9e8IAAAAIAAJ}}</ref> In 1832, he co-founded the [[Boston Lying-in Hospital]] for destitute women, now [[Brigham and Women's Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kass|first1=Amalie|title=Walter Channing|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2004/03/walter-channing.html|website=Harvard Magazine|publisher=Harvard Magazine|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> He became, in 1821, Dr. James Jackson's assistant as physician of the newly established [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], and continued there for nearly twenty years.<ref name=\"Appletons\"/> He was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1818.<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780\u20132010: Chapter C|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterC.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=September 9, 2016}}</ref> He was one of the first American physicians to employ [[anesthesia]] during childbirth, and wrote a treatise in its favor, serving as the main American advocate of the practice at the time.<ref name=\"Baas\" /><ref>{{cite journal | author = Claude E. Heaton | title = The History of Anesthesia and Analgesia in Obstetrics | journal = Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences | volume = 1 | issue = 4 | pages = 567\u2013572 | year = 1946 | doi = 10.1093/jhmas/1.4.567 | pmid = 20278344}}</ref> He was a founder and first President of the Massachusetts Society for Aiding Discharged Prisoners in 1846. The MSADP continues to follow the same objectives today. Channing died in [[Brookline, Massachusetts]].\n\n==Works==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/anaddressonprev00changoog Address on the Prevention of Pauperism]'' (1843)\n* ''Treatise on Etherization in Child-birth, illustrated by 581 cases'' (1849)\n* ''Professional Reminiscences of Foreign Travel'' (1851)\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=FyotAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false New and Old]'' (1851)\n* ''Miscellaneous Poems'' (1851)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/physiciansvacati00chan A Physician's Vacation, or a Summer in Europe]'' (1856)\n* ''Reformation of Medical Science'' (1857)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Amelie Kass]], ''Midwifery and Medicine in Boston: Walter Channing, M.D., 1786\u20131876''.  [[Northeastern University Press]], 2001.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Channing, Walter}}\n[[Category:1786 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:American obstetricians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Physicians of Massachusetts General Hospital]]\n[[Category:People from Boston]]\n[[Category:People from Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Newport, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Walter Channing''' (April 15, 1786 \u2013 July 27, 1876) was an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] and [[professor]] of [[medicine]]. He was the brother of preacher [[William Ellery Channing]] and of fellow Harvard professor (of Rhetoric), [[Edward Tyrrel Channing]]. He was also the father of the poet [[William Ellery Channing (poet)|William Ellery Channing]].  He was married to Eliza Wainwright Channing from 1831 until her death in 1834.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masshist.org/collection-guides/view/fa0018 |title=Walter Channing (1786\u20131876) Papers |author=Kathleen Barker |date=March 2002 |website=[[Massachusetts Historical Society]] |accessdate=13 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], Channing entered [[Harvard University|Harvard College]] in 1804 but was expelled because of his involvement in the \"rotten cabbage brawl\" at Harvard. After studying medicine in [[Boston]] and [[Philadelphia]], he received his diploma from the [[Univers